00:11:14,808 --> 00:11:16,675
    narrator: bourbon whiskey   
      is uniquely american.     

183
00:11:16,810 --> 00:11:19,411
        the u.s. congress       
    officially recognized it    

184
00:11:19,413 --> 00:11:21,479
          as a product          
     distinct to the nation.    

185
00:11:21,515 --> 00:11:23,882
      this amber-hued brew      
       was first cooked up      

186
00:11:24,017 --> 00:11:28,486
 by scottish and irish settlers 
 in late 18th century kentucky. 

187
00:11:28,556 --> 00:11:30,755
             today,             
   production continues there   

188
00:11:30,824 --> 00:11:32,958
 with the approval of congress. 

189
00:11:35,095 --> 00:11:38,297
     the american government    
 regulates the making of bourbon

190
00:11:38,432 --> 00:11:41,900
   to keep this native spirit   
       true to tradition.       

191
00:11:42,035 --> 00:11:43,768
     by law, it must be made    

192
00:11:43,804 --> 00:11:47,839
        from a grain mix        
    that's at least 51% corn.   

193
00:11:47,841 --> 00:11:51,776
           distillers           
   often use more for flavor.   

194
00:11:51,812 --> 00:11:55,113
      shakers sift out cobs     
   or other foreign material,   

195
00:11:55,249 --> 00:11:58,450
         and the kernels        
      head into a grinder.      

196
00:11:58,585 --> 00:12:01,119
             inside,            
    rollers crush the kernels   

197
00:12:01,155 --> 00:12:03,722
           to release           
    the flavor of the starch.   

198
00:12:03,791 --> 00:12:07,859
the process leaves larger chunks
   of the corn germ and husks.  

199
00:12:07,861 --> 00:12:11,063
         once distilled,        
   these bits will settle out.  

200
00:12:13,033 --> 00:12:14,933
in separate batches, the machine

201
00:12:15,002 --> 00:12:19,738
    also grinds malted barley   
   and soft red winter wheat.   

202
00:12:21,141 --> 00:12:22,808
 they cook the corn and blend it

203
00:12:22,810 --> 00:12:26,811
      with limestone-rich,      
    iron-free kentucky water.   

204
00:12:26,880 --> 00:12:29,081
      they add the barley,      
          winter wheat,         

205
00:12:29,116 --> 00:12:32,084
        and a bit of mash       
     from a previous batch.     

206
00:12:34,121 --> 00:12:37,289
   along with a special yeast   
   formulation, the grain mash  

207
00:12:37,424 --> 00:12:40,626
  flows into fermentation tanks 
      made of cypress wood.     

208
00:12:43,097 --> 00:12:46,698
      after 8 to 10 hours,      
    the yeast works its magic   

209
00:12:46,700 --> 00:12:49,968
          and the mash          
    becomes a bubbling brew.    

210
00:12:52,239 --> 00:12:53,438
     the bubbling is caused     

211
00:12:53,474 --> 00:12:55,974
         by the release         
      of carbon-dioxide gas     

212
00:12:56,109 --> 00:12:59,978
   as the grain sugars ferment  
       and become alcohol.      

213
00:13:00,113 --> 00:13:01,313
        after three days,       

214
00:13:01,448 --> 00:13:03,181
        it has fermented        
       into a thick liquid      

215
00:13:03,317 --> 00:13:05,450
  they call 'distiller's beer." 

216
00:13:07,187 --> 00:13:11,189
they pump it into a column still
  which boils off the alcohol,  

217
00:13:11,325 --> 00:13:14,392
          leaving water         
  and other substances behind.  

218
00:13:14,428 --> 00:13:17,863
  the alcoholic vapor rises up  
  to be condensed into liquid.  

219
00:13:17,998 --> 00:13:20,932
       after distilling it      
         a second time,         

220
00:13:20,968 --> 00:13:25,704
    the alcohol concentration   
  rises to a strong 130 proof.  

221
00:13:29,109 --> 00:13:32,077
           it's clear,          
    with no noticeable color.   

222
00:13:32,146 --> 00:13:34,646
         at this stage,         
    they call it "white dog."   

223
00:13:35,882 --> 00:13:38,216
    once water has been added   
      to dilute the whiskey     

224
00:13:38,285 --> 00:13:40,218
          to 110 proof,         

225
00:13:40,220 --> 00:13:44,889
   an employee takes a sample   
    and sends it to the lab.    

226
00:13:44,958 --> 00:13:48,293
   there, a technician places   
   a test tube of the alcohol   

227
00:13:48,428 --> 00:13:51,296
into a gas chromatograph tester.

228
00:13:53,901 --> 00:13:55,767
    it vaporizes the alcohol    

229
00:13:55,902 --> 00:13:59,905
  and then analyzes the flavor  
 compounds and alcohol strength.

230
00:14:01,809 --> 00:14:03,708
   with approval from the lab,  

231
00:14:03,777 --> 00:14:07,045
          they're ready         
      to barrel the batch.      

232
00:14:07,047 --> 00:14:10,047
   they pump it out of storage  
 tanks and into new oak barrels 

233
00:14:10,084 --> 00:14:14,519
that have been purposely charred
         on the inside.         

234
00:14:14,521 --> 00:14:17,589
      charring caramelizes      
 naturally occurring wood sugars

235
00:14:17,591 --> 00:14:21,993
        to add sweetness        
   to the alcohol as it ages.   

236
00:14:22,062 --> 00:14:25,697
   it will also turn the clear  
     alcohol an amber color.    

237
00:14:29,269 --> 00:14:31,670
           once corked          
     with a walnut stopper,     

238
00:14:31,805 --> 00:14:36,875
  the employee rolls the barrel 
 into a multi-tiered warehouse. 

239
00:14:37,010 --> 00:14:39,878
        here, the bourbon       
    will age for many years.    

240
00:14:39,880 --> 00:14:41,279
        partway through,        

241
00:14:41,315 --> 00:14:43,415
     they'll move the barrel    
to another level of the building

242
00:14:43,550 --> 00:14:46,017
 due to temperature variations. 

243
00:14:46,086 --> 00:14:49,754
   this will make the product   
        more consistent.        

244
00:14:49,823 --> 00:14:51,956
    after six to seven years,   

245
00:14:51,959 --> 00:14:55,093
     they uncork the stopper    
     and insert steel tubes     

246
00:14:55,095 --> 00:14:57,329
     to draw in ambient air.    

247
00:14:59,032 --> 00:15:02,033
     this causes the bourbon    
   to flow freely when tipped,  

248
00:15:02,102 --> 00:15:05,036
  and it gushes into a trough.  

249
00:15:05,072 --> 00:15:09,307
     the alcohol has ripened    
to a sweet caramel-colored brew.

250
00:15:12,012 --> 00:15:14,980
    after they add more water   
      to make it 90 proof,      

251
00:15:14,982 --> 00:15:17,449
    it's ready for bottling.    

252
00:15:17,584 --> 00:15:20,986
    nozzles fill the bottles    
 with bourbon right to the neck.

253
00:15:24,024 --> 00:15:28,527
     the bottles then circle    
  over to the cap applicators.  

254
00:15:28,662 --> 00:15:33,231
the applicators spin metal caps,
 screwing them onto the bottles.

255
00:15:35,102 --> 00:15:36,935
the bottles then ride a carousel

256
00:15:37,070 --> 00:15:40,538
          and a device          
picks up and applies the labels.

257
00:15:40,574 --> 00:15:43,542
      a brush smoothes them     
         to the bottles.        

258
00:15:45,779 --> 00:15:48,213
down the line, a two-person team

259
00:15:48,215 --> 00:15:53,084
      retrieves the bottles     
  and dips the caps in hot wax. 

260
00:15:53,153 --> 00:15:56,287
    the wax quickly dries and   
 solidifies to give the bourbon 

261
00:15:56,323 --> 00:15:58,190
         a better seal.         

262
00:16:00,961 --> 00:16:03,361
       after several years      
       in the distillery,       

263
00:16:03,497 --> 00:16:06,631
      this kentucky bourbon     
        has come of age,        

264
00:16:06,667 --> 00:16:09,134
   and that calls for a toast.  

265
00:16:25,385 --> 00:16:27,319
   narrator: the circuit board  

266
00:16:27,321 --> 00:16:29,454
     is where the electronic    
     components are located,    

267
00:16:29,456 --> 00:16:31,389
    along with the electrical   
  connections which power them. 

268
00:16:31,425 --> 00:16:33,858
       in a larger device,      
       such as a computer,      

269
00:16:33,927 --> 00:16:35,860
        the circuit board       
       is typically rigid.      

270
00:16:35,929 --> 00:16:38,596
   when the device is compact,  
      like a small camera,      

271
00:16:38,632 --> 00:16:40,932
        the circuit board       
        must be flexible.       

272
00:16:40,934 --> 00:16:43,502
 it needs to fold to fit inside.

273
00:16:45,138 --> 00:16:48,073
     flexible circuit boards    
    are so thin and pliable,    

274
00:16:48,208 --> 00:16:50,542
        they're nicknamed       
       origami circuitry,       

275
00:16:50,611 --> 00:16:54,078
     after the japanese art     
        of paper folding.       

276
00:16:54,114 --> 00:16:57,749
    at the core of the boards   
   is a hair-thin polymer film  

277
00:16:57,784 --> 00:17:00,218
      that's both bendable      
       and heat resistant.      

278
00:17:00,353 --> 00:17:04,489
 the manufacturer produces this 
material for several industries.

279
00:17:04,624 --> 00:17:06,691
          in this case,         
      they cut rolls of it      

280
00:17:06,693 --> 00:17:10,362
to the width required for making
    flexible circuit boards.    

281
00:17:12,632 --> 00:17:16,434
   with a rigid sheet of paper  
lending support from underneath,

282
00:17:16,436 --> 00:17:17,969
    the film enters a machine   

283
00:17:18,005 --> 00:17:21,305
   which sandwiches it between  
   two thin sheets of copper.   

284
00:17:21,341 --> 00:17:23,174
          a cutter then         
       slices the sandwich      

285
00:17:23,210 --> 00:17:25,377
    into rectangular sheets.    

286
00:17:25,379 --> 00:17:27,679
        a cushion of air        
pumped through the conveyor belt

287
00:17:27,748 --> 00:17:30,982
     literally floats sheet     
   after sheet off the machine  

288
00:17:30,984 --> 00:17:34,185
        and into a stack.       

289
00:17:34,187 --> 00:17:36,854
     each three-layer sheet     
   is separated from the next   

290
00:17:36,924 --> 00:17:40,592
      by the support paper      
       called a laminate.       

291
00:17:40,661 --> 00:17:44,262
  the film at the center has a  
heat-activated adhesive coating,

292
00:17:44,397 --> 00:17:46,331
       while the adjoining      
         copper surfaces        

293
00:17:46,400 --> 00:17:49,868
 have been chemically roughened 
      to enhance adhesion.      

294
00:17:50,003 --> 00:17:53,271
    after drawing the layers    
 tightly together with a vacuum,

295
00:17:53,273 --> 00:17:54,805
   workers place the laminates  

296
00:17:54,841 --> 00:17:57,208
     in a high-temperature,     
      high-pressure chamber     

297
00:17:57,244 --> 00:17:59,010
       for several hours.       

298
00:17:59,079 --> 00:18:02,948
  this activates the adhesive,  
       bonding the layers.      

299
00:18:03,083 --> 00:18:04,815
   to test the bond strength,   

300
00:18:04,885 --> 00:18:08,152
   they burn some adhesive off  
  a sample of finished laminate 

301
00:18:08,188 --> 00:18:11,155
 to pry apart the layered edge. 

302
00:18:11,258 --> 00:18:14,759
 then, they grab the top copper 
 layer with this pulling device 

303
00:18:14,761 --> 00:18:16,761
    and measure the strength    
        required to peel        

304
00:18:16,763 --> 00:18:18,697
        it off the film.        

305
00:18:18,832 --> 00:18:21,966
   the laminate's now shipped   
   to a circuit board factory.  

306
00:18:21,969 --> 00:18:23,835
 here, computer-guided machines 

307
00:18:23,904 --> 00:18:26,104
            cut them            
   into specific-sized panels   

308
00:18:26,106 --> 00:18:27,839
      and drill tiny holes      
          for mounting          

309
00:18:27,841 --> 00:18:29,841
   the electronic components.   

310
00:18:31,311 --> 00:18:32,510
     then a coating machine     

311
00:18:32,512 --> 00:18:35,246
       uses a combination       
      of heat and pressure      

312
00:18:35,282 --> 00:18:39,116
to apply a light-sensitive fluid
     to the panel's surface.    

313
00:18:39,152 --> 00:18:42,520
   technicians load the panel   
    into an exposure machine,   

314
00:18:42,522 --> 00:18:46,124
in which a computer-guided laser
   scans the circuitry pattern  

315
00:18:46,126 --> 00:18:47,859
     onto the coded surface.    

316
00:18:47,928 --> 00:18:50,328
        a laser is a beam       
        of focused light,       

317
00:18:50,463 --> 00:18:54,732
      so wherever it hits,      
  the fluid reacts and hardens. 

318
00:18:54,768 --> 00:18:59,070
         the dark areas         
 of unexposed fluid remain soft.

319
00:18:59,072 --> 00:19:02,540
        the next machine        
   acid-washes the soft areas,  

320
00:19:02,609 --> 00:19:04,142
     removing both the fluid    

321
00:19:04,211 --> 00:19:06,077
      and the copper layer      
         underneath it.         

322
00:19:06,212 --> 00:19:09,614
  now the only copper remaining 
   on top of the polymer film   

323
00:19:09,683 --> 00:19:12,083
  is in the circuitry pattern.  

324
00:19:12,218 --> 00:19:13,418
     this inspection device     

325
00:19:13,553 --> 00:19:17,322
       meticulously checks      
  every single copper circuit.  

326
00:19:18,659 --> 00:19:22,227
 next, they remove surface dust 
      with a sticky roller.     

327
00:19:22,362 --> 00:19:23,828
   the panel must be pristine   

328
00:19:23,963 --> 00:19:26,698
   before receiving the sheet   
    of electrical insulation,   

329
00:19:26,800 --> 00:19:31,436
   a mere .25 of a millimeter   
             thick.             

330
00:19:31,571 --> 00:19:33,371
   technicians use a magnifier  

331
00:19:33,440 --> 00:19:36,040
      to carefully match up     
   alignment holes on the film  

332
00:19:36,109 --> 00:19:39,110
       with corresponding       
  alignment holes on the panel. 

333
00:19:39,179 --> 00:19:41,579
          by activating         
  the film's built-in adhesive  

334
00:19:41,615 --> 00:19:43,114
     with a soldering iron,     

335
00:19:43,183 --> 00:19:47,786
    they tack the insulation    
   to the panel at key spots.   

336
00:19:47,788 --> 00:19:50,321
    the next step is to fully   
     laminate the insulation    

337
00:19:50,424 --> 00:19:51,589
          to the panel.         

338
00:19:51,725 --> 00:19:53,391
 technicians sandwich two panels

339
00:19:53,460 --> 00:19:56,728
    at a time between sheets    
     of protective plastic.     

340
00:19:56,797 --> 00:19:59,263
   this protects the surfaces   
    from the heat and weight    

341
00:19:59,332 --> 00:20:01,599
    of the lamination press.    

342
00:20:01,635 --> 00:20:04,936
as it forces the insulation film
    deep down onto the panel,   

343
00:20:05,071 --> 00:20:08,272
 it encapsulates the circuitry. 

344
00:20:08,308 --> 00:20:10,808
      they load the panels      
   into the lamination press,   

345
00:20:10,844 --> 00:20:14,279
    apply a vacuum to remove    
   the air between the layers   

346
00:20:14,414 --> 00:20:16,413
        and start her up.       

347
00:20:16,450 --> 00:20:18,483
  for the next hour and a half, 

348
00:20:18,518 --> 00:20:21,686
    the press simultaneously    
      applies high pressure     

349
00:20:21,688 --> 00:20:26,024
    while heating the panels    
   to 400 degrees fahrenheit.   

350
00:20:26,159 --> 00:20:29,226
      when the panels cool      
   and come out of the press,   

351
00:20:29,262 --> 00:20:34,465
 technicians place one at a time
 on a circuit board-shaped dye. 

352
00:20:34,501 --> 00:20:36,167
    then they release a press   

353
00:20:36,302 --> 00:20:38,903
     which forces the panel     
       onto the sharp dye,      

354
00:20:38,972 --> 00:20:42,240
          slicing away          
      the excess material.      

355
00:20:42,242 --> 00:20:45,176
   the flexible circuit board   
  is now ready for the company  

356
00:20:45,178 --> 00:20:48,012
          that installs         
   the electronic components.   

357
00:20:51,284 --> 00:20:53,851
       there are two ways       
     to mount components --     

358
00:20:53,954 --> 00:20:56,654
      solder them directly      
    onto the board's surface    

359
00:20:56,723 --> 00:20:58,323
      or solder tiny prongs     

360
00:20:58,458 --> 00:21:00,525
   underneath the components,   
         known as leads,        

361
00:21:00,594 --> 00:21:02,993
into the board's mounting holes.

362
00:21:03,029 --> 00:21:04,395
    a flexible circuit board    

363
00:21:04,397 --> 00:21:07,064
         can have as few        
      as a dozen components     

364
00:21:07,134 --> 00:21:09,868
       or as many as 500.       

365
00:21:09,870 --> 00:21:11,068
     technicians can solder     

366
00:21:11,138 --> 00:21:14,739
           larger ones          
  magnified under a microscope, 

367
00:21:14,874 --> 00:21:17,808
         but only robots        
     can solder smaller ones    

368
00:21:17,844 --> 00:21:19,477
     because they're so tiny    

369
00:21:19,546 --> 00:21:22,247
       and barely visible       
        to the human eye.       

